<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,508,895]" pageId="1" pageNumber="431">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,751,652,677]" pageId="1" pageNumber="431">Variations on the specimens examined (n = 3).</emphasis>
The mesostigmal plates illustrated here (
<figureCitation box="[1216,1324,652,677]" captionStart="FIGURES 2‒3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,648,671]" captionTargetBox="[176,1389,223,624]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[159,1427,193,628]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2‒3. Argia bicellulata (Calvert) BRAZIL: &quot;Chapada&quot; (paralectotype) mesostigmal lobes; 2. anterior view; 3. dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250847/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="431">Figs. 2‒3</figureCitation>
) are from Calvert's single female. No variation on mesostigmal plate morphology was detected, comparing our specimens to figures of Calvert's female (
<figureCitation box="[476,588,724,749]" captionStart="FIGURES 2‒3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,648,671]" captionTargetBox="[176,1389,223,624]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[159,1427,193,628]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2‒3. Argia bicellulata (Calvert) BRAZIL: &quot;Chapada&quot; (paralectotype) mesostigmal lobes; 2. anterior view; 3. dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250847/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="431">Figs. 2‒3</figureCitation>
); Wing venation: no variation RP2 branching and postquadrangular cells; postnodal varied as follows: 
<quantity box="[482,574,762,787]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.667" metricValueMax="2.794" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="1" pageNumber="431" unit="in" value="10.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="10.0">10–11in</quantity>
Fw and 
<quantity box="[678,765,762,787]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" metricValueMax="2.794" metricValueMin="2.286" pageId="1" pageNumber="431" unit="in" value="10.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="9.0">9–11 in</quantity>
Hw (
<tableCitation box="[831,917,762,787]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,239,942,965]" captionText="TABLE 1. Venation statistics for Argia bicellulata examined by Calvert (1909) and in this study." pageId="1" pageNumber="431">Table 1</tableCitation>
); size varied as follows: abdomen 18.3–20.2 (19.1±0.9), total length 23.3–25.9 (24.2±1.4), Fw 14.3–14.9 (14.5±0.3), Hw 13.8–14.6 (14±0.4). Body coloration had little variation on the specimens examined (
<figureCitation box="[686,807,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURES 4‒11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1422,1445]" captionTargetBox="[252,1328,774,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[149,1420,734,1391]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4‒11. Argia bicellulata (Calvert) BRAZIL: Chapada dos Guimarães; 4. S1‒10, ♀ (ACR 3322); 5. S1‒10, ♀ (ACR 3326); 6. S8‒10, ♀ (ACR 3326); 7. S8‒10, ♀ (ACR 3322); 8. thorax, ♀ (ACR 3322); 9. thorax, ♀ (ACR 3326); 10. head, ♀ (ACR 3326); 11. head, ♀ (ACR 3322)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250849/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="431">Figs. 4–11</figureCitation>
), being more visible on the slightly different post ocular spots coloration (
<figureCitation box="[344,480,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 4‒11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1422,1445]" captionTargetBox="[252,1328,774,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[149,1420,734,1391]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4‒11. Argia bicellulata (Calvert) BRAZIL: Chapada dos Guimarães; 4. S1‒10, ♀ (ACR 3322); 5. S1‒10, ♀ (ACR 3326); 6. S8‒10, ♀ (ACR 3326); 7. S8‒10, ♀ (ACR 3322); 8. thorax, ♀ (ACR 3322); 9. thorax, ♀ (ACR 3326); 10. head, ♀ (ACR 3326); 11. head, ♀ (ACR 3322)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1250849/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="431">Figs. 10–11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
